    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="121"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/632</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Langhorne</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 7, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 1.45 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>961. Department’s circular 2d [<hi rend="italic">1st</hi>]. In <hi rend="italic"
                        >Vossische Zeitung</hi>, 6th, <persName>Georg Bernhard</persName> referring
                    to statement <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">Gerard</persName> made public by this
                    Legation says: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>I can readily understand that my statement is very embarrassing to Mr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">Gerard</persName> but he can not dispose
                            of it by simple denial. It is fact that he repeatedly made statements
                            identical with what I wrote in article 24th. My interviews with
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">Gerard</persName> were always very
                            extended and often lasted several hours. I discussed with him as well as
                            with <persName corresp="#p_PFC1">Penfield</persName> when I was in
                            Vienna the possibilities of mediation by <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                                >Wilson</persName>. The gentlemen knew I was quite opposed to such
                            mediation and naturally it was <persName corresp="#p_GJW2"
                                >Gerard</persName>’s object to make it clear to me how advantageous
                            such mediation would be to us. In these conversations it became quite
                            clear to me that America’s interests were wholly identical with
                            England’s and that President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                                >Wilson</persName> was trying to arrange peace favorable to England
                            if only for the sake of their financial consolidation. It was then only
                            natural to proclaim America’s agreement to German land acquisition in
                            the east in order induce Germany to renounce all indemnity in land or
                            money in west. This was always the pith of <persName corresp="#p_GJW2"
                                >Gerard</persName>’s remarks which revealed complete lack of
                            interest in Russia’s fate. I was not for a moment in doubt that
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">Gerard</persName> felt himself
                            completely in agreement with President on this point. Russia was to be
                            sacrificed by England as permanent hatred between Germany and Russia was
                            believed valuable political asset.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Langhorne</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
